  "slug": "beef-goulash",
  "title": "Beef goulash",
  "subtitle": "Hungarian beef stew, thick with sweet paprika and onion.",
  "excerpt": "Beef shin braised low and slow with a great deal of sweet paprika, onion, caraway and green pepper until the sauce is thick, richly coloured and the meat is falling apart. Hungary's national stew. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Hungarian beef goulash (gulyás). The dish originates with Hungarian cattle herders and first appeared as a national dish in cookbooks in the 19th century. August Escoffier documented a version in Le Guide Culinaire (1903, public domain). The dish is central to Hungarian national identity; the Austro-Hungarian Empire spread versions of it across Central Europe.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Goulash uses a remarkable quantity of paprika, far more than feels instinctive. Three tablespoons of sweet paprika is the correct amount for four people, not a half teaspoon. The paprika is the dish. It must go into hot fat and be stirred for 30 seconds before the liquid is added, to bloom the flavour; it must not be skimped.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Hungarian sweet paprika is different from smoked paprika. Use proper Hungarian paprika if possible; it is milder and sweeter than other varieties. The combination of sweet and smoked paprika here approximates the flavour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
