        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the onion and bloom the paprika",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{lard}} of lard in a large casserole over medium heat. Cook {{onion}} diced onion for 12 minutes until very soft and beginning to caramelise. Add {{garlic}} of chopped garlic and {{pepper-green}} diced green pepper; cook 3 minutes. Remove from the heat. Stir in {{paprika-sweet}} of sweet paprika, {{paprika-smoked}} of smoked paprika and {{caraway-seeds}} of caraway seeds. Return to low heat and stir for 30 seconds.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add beef and simmer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add {{beef-shin}} of beef cubes, {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée, {{stock-beef}} of stock, {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Bring to a simmer, cover, and cook on the lowest possible heat for 1.5 to 2 hours until the beef is very tender and the sauce is thick and coating. Remove the bay leaves. Serve with soured cream.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "This dish needs 3 tablespoons of paprika; it is not a mistake. Bloom the paprika in hot fat before adding any liquid.",
              "cause": "Not enough paprika, or liquid added before paprika bloomed.",
              "symptom": "Sauce thin and pale"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the pan from the heat before adding paprika. It blooms from residual heat; 30 seconds off the heat is safer than 30 seconds on.",
              "cause": "Paprika burned in the fat before liquid was added.",
              "symptom": "Paprika tastes bitter"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cut beef to 4 cm maximum. Keep the heat at the lowest setting; a vigorous boil makes the beef tough.",
              "cause": "Pieces too large, or simmering too vigorously.",
              "symptom": "Beef still tough at 2 hours"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Goulash is the national dish of Hungary, rooted in the cattle-herding tradition of the Great Plain and carried across Central Europe by the Austro-Hungarian Empire. Every country with a connection to that history has a version. The Hungarian original is the simplest and most austere: beef, onion and paprika, nothing more. Serve with egg noodles, soured cream and a cold beer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
